06247nam a22008415i 9781474468213DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222002stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744682137 a10.1515/97814744682132doi  a(DE-B1597)615469  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a320.0112211 aFinlayson, Alan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics and Post-Structuralism :bAn Introduction /cAlan Finlayson, Jeremy Valentine. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Politics and the Subject -- t1 The Subject and Subjectivity -- t2 The Theoretical Link Between Politics and the Subject -- t3 The State and Sovereign Subjectivity -- t4 After the Subject of International Security -- tPart Two Doing Political Analysis -- t5 Ideology and Social Movements: the case of the FN -- t6 The Work of Ideas and Interests in Public Policy -- t7 Globalisation and the Constitution of Political Economy -- t8 Complexity in the Wild: action in local welfare -- t9 Political Science and Complexity -- tPart Three Critique and Political Thought -- t10 The Horizon of Community -- t11 Critical Theory and Democracy -- t12 The Singularity of the Political -- t13 Genres, Technologies and Spaces of Being-In-Common -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPost-structuralism is recognised as a major force within literary and cultural studies. This book is the first to apply the theory to politics and to show the ways in which it can illuminate political theory and analysis. As such it is likely to become a key text in the development of this area, providing a stimulating introduction to the subject. Authors explore the two-way relationship, showing not only that post-structuralism can enhance the study of politics, but also that advocates of post-structuralism can benefit from being open to the lessons political studies can teach. The book aims to (i) clarify the relationship of contemporary theory to politics; (ii) open up a new intellectual interface; (iii) create a space for exchange between disciplines; (iv) provide a statement of the role of post-structuralist theory in politicsCovering three main sections - What is Post-structuralist Political Theory?; Post-structuralism and Political Analysis; and The Question of the Political - the authors draw on themes raised by Continental thinkers such as Derrida, Nancy and Deleuze, and Anglo-American thinkers such as Butler and Connolly in their questioning of the theoretical and empirical understanding of contemporary politics.Key Features First systematic examination of post-structuralism to see what it may mean for political studies Advances its own rigorous and theoretically informed position Cutting edge: provides a vibrant introduction to this area of political thought and analysis Brings clarity to the two-way relationship between post-structuralism and politics  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPolitical science. 0aPoststructuralism. 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh1 aBastovo, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Glyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevenney, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdkins, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinlayson, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriggs, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https:/